languages: The Italian language originated from Vulgar Latin, a language spoken during the Middle Ages. Vulgar Latin was derived from Latin, but it was simpler and more widespread than Classical Latin, which was used by writers and scholars. Vulgar Latin spread extensively starting in the 6th and 7th centuries, and it eventually developed into the Italian language. The use of Vulgar Latin in public situations began with notaries, merchants, and religious figures who wanted to communicate more effectively with the general population. While Classical Latin remained the official language of the Church, Vulgar Latin became a key tool for spreading the Catholic faith. In the 13th century, Vulgar Latin became firmly established as a literary language, marking the beginning of the development of the Italian language.
